{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.07,0.17,0.09,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/197"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"6061"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman is admitted to hospital after a motor vehicle accident in which she sustained a fractured right femur and left humerus. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. After initial resuscitation, the fractures are treated by open reduction and internal fixation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring surgery, she becomes cyanosed without apparent trigger. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. She has a petechial rash on her chest. Her chest is clear with no wheeze. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial blood gas (room air): pH 7.45, PaO2 40 mmHg (80-100), PaCO2 27 mmHg (35-45). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray, which was normal at admission, now shows bilateral infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular adrenaline","Intravenous methylprednisolone","Therapeutic heparin","Broad-spectrum antibiotics","Oxygen therapy and supportive care"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic signs of fat embolism syndrome (FES): hypoxaemia and petechial rash. FES typically occurs within 24-72 hours after long bone fractures, particularly of the femur. The diagnosis is supported by the acute onset during surgery, normal white cell count, and bilateral infiltrates on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen therapy and supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E is the mainstay of treatment for FES. This includes maintaining oxygenation (which may require mechanical ventilation), ensuring adequate fluid balance, and monitoring for complications. No specific treatment has been proven to prevent or treat FES effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for anaphylaxis, but this patient\u0027s presentation is not consistent with anaphylaxis. There is no bronchospasm, angioedema, or cardiovascular collapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E has been studied in FES but has not shown consistent benefit. While some studies suggest a possible preventive role, there is insufficient evidence to recommend routine corticosteroid use in established FES.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic heparin\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for pulmonary embolism, but the presence of a petechial rash and the timing after long bone fracture make FES much more likely than pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad-spectrum antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for sepsis, but the normal white cell count, timing of onset, and characteristic features of FES make infection unlikely as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fat embolism syndrome classically presents with hypoxia, petechial rash, and confusion within 24-72 hours of long bone fracture.","Supportive care including oxygen therapy and ventilation is the mainstay of treatment for fat embolism syndrome.","No specific pharmacological therapy has been proven effective in treating fat embolism syndrome."],"references":["Kwiatt ME, Seamon MJ. Fat embolism syndrome. Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci. 2013 Jan;3(1):64-8. doi: 10.4103/2229-5151.109426. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23724388/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62696"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:17:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T11:17:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"197"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisi